[2]
Date: Thu, 19 Dec 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Scotsman.com, 19 Dec 2002 [edited]
<http://www.news.scotsman.com/scotland.cfm?id=1412302002>

Plant illegally burned BSE-infected carcases
--------------------------------------------
Politicians yesterday called for an inquiry into the use of animal
incinerators across Scotland after hearing warnings that they could be
illegally burning BSE-infected carcasses. The move comes after it emerged
that one incinerator in Glasgow had burned 2 BSE carcasses even though it
was not licensed to do so.
Yesterday, Ross Finnie, the environment minister, confirmed that the
burnings had taken place at the Carntyne plant, which local residents are
campaigning to have closed down. Homeowners in the city's East End have
voiced concerns about health issues arising from the incinerator's
operation and have raised the subject in a petition to the Scottish
Parliament. Now the Parliament's environment committee has backed a report
from one of its members calling for a review of the issue north of the Border.
Only 2 plants in Scotland are allowed to burn BSE-infected carcasses while
permission for the other 6, including Carntyne, rule this out. But as tests
on cattle for BSE can take between 10 and 14 days, most carcasses are
burned before the results come back.
Mr Finnie told the committee reporter yesterday that this situation has led
to 2 known incidents in which BSE-infected cattle have been burned at
Carntyne between September 2001 and March 2002.
The plant, which reopened after a 4-year closure in May 2002, had
originally been licensed to burn BSE-infected cattle, but was forced to
stop after the previous owner, Westcot Hides, breached government
regulations on emissions.
The report, outlined to MSPs [Members of Scottish parliament] on the Mound
yesterday, said it was believed that plants across Scotland were
"circumventing planning conditions".
The Scottish Environmental Protection Agency (SEPA), the environmental
watchdog, had already responded by setting incinerator temperatures at 850C
to destroy the BSE prion, the report added. It stated: "There is little
merit setting a planning condition that the planning authority cannot
enforce and which in practice SEPA enforces. The reporter therefore
recommends that SEPA should have a statutory role in the process for
regulating BSE."
The report continued: "The reporter recommends that SEPA should assume that
all animal carcass incinerators in Scotland may be burning BSE-infected
cattle and license and regulate incinerators on that basis."
More than 47 500 people lived within a one-mile radius of the Carntyne
incinerator, which is thought to be the only one in the UK to operate in an
urban area. There are 117 schools and colleges, 12 nursery schools, 2
hospitals, 23 nursing homes, and 34 health centres as well as doctors'
surgeries within the area.
Last year, 5 months after the plant was reopened, it was forced to close
for 3 months following complaints from residents that the smell and ash
from there was affecting them.
However, Sacone Environmental, which runs the Carntyne plant, was granted
permission by SEPA to burn cattle again just before last Christmas. No one
from Sacone Environmental was available for comment last night.
[Byline: John Staples]
