[3]
Date: Thu, 19 Dec 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Financial Times, 19 Dec 2002 [edited]
<http://news.ft.com/servlet/ContentServer?pagename=FT.com/StoryFT/FullStory&c=StoryFT&cid=1039523814967>

Restaurant managers held over UK beef imports
----------------------------------------------
French prosecutors yesterday detained 4 senior managers of the Buffalo
Grill restaurant chain under suspicion of illegally importing British beef
infected with mad cow disease.
Among those being held in custody for questioning were Christian Picart,
chief executive. The others were the head of the company's purchasing arm
and 2 managers from its Districoupe unit, which supplies meat to the
group's 260 restaurants across Europe.
They were detained as part of a 2-year judicial inquiry to investigate
complaints of "manslaughter, involuntary injury, and placing the lives of
others in danger" from victims of CJD, the human variant of BSE, or mad cow
disease.
In France 4 people have died from CJD, and a fifth person is believed to
have the disease. There have been 117 confirmed and probable deaths in
Britain from CJD.
France banned imports of British beef in 1996. The ban was lifted in
October 2002, more than 2 years after the European Union had lifted its
ban, prompting Britain to take France to the European Court of Justice.
There have been suspicions that cheap British beef found its way on to the
French market in the early period after the ban was imposed.
French police are understood to have found that 2 of the victims of CJD
regularly dined at Buffalo Grill restaurants. The company denied it had
illegally imported beef. "A group as big as ours cannot allow itself to do
that. It would be suicidal and fatal."
[Byline: Martin Arnold]
