[SEAC, established 10 years ago, is required to provide scientifically
based advice to relevant official authorities, including the Department for
Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (DEFRA), the Department of Health (MOH)
and the Food Standards Agency (FSA) on matters relating to spongiform
encephalopathies, taking into account the input of other bodies with
related responsibilities. This experts' committee is composed of 13
members, including 3 scientists from other countries (Australia,
Switzerland, and the USA). SEAC's current (since August 2001) chairman is
Peter G Smith, Professor of Tropical Epidemiology at the London School of
Hygiene and Tropical Medicine. Prof Stanley Prusiner's advice has been
sought by SEAC on various TSE-related issues. The research mentioned by
Prof Prusiner has been published by P.J.Bosque et al in Proc Natl Acad Sci
U S A 2002 Mar 19;99(6):3812-7. The abstract can be seen at
<http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&list_uids=11904434&dopt=Abstract>.
One of the other issues discussed during the recent SEAC meeting in London
(14 Nov 2002) was an FSA-funded project that seeks to determine whether
infectious prions can be detected in the milk of cattle experimentally
infected with the BSE agent. The final report, conclusions and
recommendations of this important research, which started in Sep 2000, are
expected at the end of 2004. SEAC will hold its next periodic meeting on 11
Feb 2003. Information on SEAC meetings and relevant documents can be found at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/bse/bse-science/SEAC2/meetings.htm>
- Mod.AS]
